    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "# **Model 1: Decision Tree**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "rhqgkWeHVYuf"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**Parametric model**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "p13rIAb5jBef"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "A parametric model, such as a linear regression model, carries a predetermined number of parameters, so its degrees of freedom are limited, reducing the risk of overfitting (but increasing the risk of underfitting)."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "jWSOOzn4m0wQ"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**Nonparametric model** *(ATTENTION: This is a ML specific term! In econometrics/statistics this means something else!)*:"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "B-suIzvhm6Q3"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "The number of parameters is not determined prior to training, so the model structure is free to stick closely to the data.\n",
        "An unconstrained\n",
        "decision tree illustrates this clearly: given sufficient depth and\n",
        "no minimum node size, it will recursively partition the training data\n",
        "until every leaf contains a single observation, achieving zero\n",
        "in-sample error.\n",
        "SO...If left unconstrained, the tree structure will adapt itself to the training data, fitting it very closely: overfitting = low bias at the cost of very high variance."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "CC2jlPtSm_kj"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**AS USUAL... A TRADE-OFF BETWEEN MEAN AND VARIANCE WILL EXIST!**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "c4W8OESGie6t"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "| Model type | Bias | Variance | Risk |\n",
        "|---|---|---|---|\n",
        "| Parametric (linear regression, fixed structure) | High bias | Low variance | Underfitting |\n",
        "| Nonparametric (unconstrained tree) | Low bias | High variance | Overfitting |"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "w4gCBl-snZ1h"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**We want to reduce the risk of overfitting...**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "tz4LJxhho5Ex"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**Pruning** is the generic term\n",
        "for any technique that limits tree complexity, trading some bias for a\n",
        "reduction in variance."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "z2SFVq4gn86Q"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "*1) Pre-pruning*"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "o2Mk1D1hpASn"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "Pre-pruning constrains tree growth while it is being built by\n",
        "imposing stopping rules on the splitting procedure. We tune two hyperparameters that act as pre-pruning\n",
        "devices:"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "XUseL6Eyr4U0"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "*   `max_depth` $⟶$ the maximum number of levels from the tree’s root node down to its deepest leaf. Shallow trees: high-bias vs. deep trees: high vairance. When we set the `max_depth` to `None` then:\n",
        "a) tree is grown until all leaves are pure (which in practice for continuous targets means each leaf contains a single observation) or b) contain fewer than `min_samples_split` samples\n",
        "\n",
        "*   `min_samples_split` $⟶$ the minimum number of training samples that a node must have before it’s allowed to split. In other words, it enforces a minimum number of training observations that a node\n",
        "must contain before it is eligible to be split further. Larger values prevent the tree from creating very small, data-specific partitions in sparse regions of the feature space."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "V7DM5PV8c2uz"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**N.B.** Although pre-pruning is computationally cheap,\n",
        "note that it is ``too short-sighted'': a split that appears useless\n",
        "in isolation may enable highly informative splits two or three levels\n",
        "below it, so greedy stopping can discard genuinely useful structure."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "33Paqo5umc5t"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "*2) Post-pruning (Cost-Complexity Pruning)*"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "CNIw6fGepfEw"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "Post-pruning first grows the maximal tree $T_0$, then collapses internal nodes by minimising the cost-complexity criterion $C_\\alpha(T) = \\sum_{m=1}^{|T|} N_m Q_m(T) + \\alpha|T|$, which penalises both training error and tree size so that larger $\\alpha$ yields smaller subtrees. The optimal subtree is found by **weakest-link** pruning: nodes are collapsed in order of the smallest per-node error increase, producing a sequence $T_0 \\supset T_1 \\supset \\cdots \\supset T_K$ with corresponding complexity values $\\alpha_0 < \\alpha_1 < \\cdots < \\alpha_K$ returned by `cost_complexity_pruning_path()`. The optimal $\\alpha^*$ is then selected by choosing the value that minimises the average validation MSE across the five time-series cross-validation folds."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "jcgToAP5msdX"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "*What do we do?*"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "JP7LRoKvny-B"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "In our implementation pre-pruning is the primary regularisation strategy. Pre-pruning parameters control the bias-variance tradeoff, but the optimal point on that tradeoff depends entirely on the data.\n",
        "\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "2GYRljygn3Bf"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "*The grid search tunes `max_depth` and `min_samples_split` simultaneously with `TimeSeriesSplit` cross-validation.*"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "xNlwycZeoW7J"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "dt_param_grid = {\n",
        "    \"max_depth\": [2, 3, 5, 10, None],\n",
        "    \"min_samples_split\": [2, 10, 50, 100]\n",
        "}\n",
        "dt_results = []"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "0AYMHTA6IqlH"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "*What does the grid search actually do ?*"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "v2Uox-6WoiRz"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "Within each fold the scaler is re-fitted exclusively on the training portion to prevent information leakage from the validation set. The combination that minimises the average MSE across the five folds is selected and used to train the final model on train+val set."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "toC8voJdqROU"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        " It empirically estimates the generalisation error for each combination using held-out validation data. For **example**...\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "C5dIZAYgolri"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "| `max_depth` | `min_samples_split` | Avg validation MSE (across the 5 folds!)|\n",
        "|---|---|---|\n",
        "| 2 | 2 | 0.51 |\n",
        "| 2 | 10 | 0.48 |\n",
        "| 2 | 50 | 0.47 |\n",
        "| 2 | 100 | 0.46 |\n",
        "| 3 | 2 | 0.44 |\n",
        "| 3 | 10 | 0.42 |\n",
        "| 3 | 50 | 0.39 |\n",
        "| 3 | 100 | 0.40 |\n",
        "| 5 | 2 | 0.41 |\n",
        "| **5** | **10** | **0.38 ← best** |\n",
        "| 5 | 50 | 0.41 |\n",
        "| 5 | 100 | 0.43 |\n",
        "| 10 | 2 | 0.45 |\n",
        "| 10 | 10 | 0.44 |\n",
        "| 10 | 50 | 0.42 |\n",
        "| 10 | 100 | 0.43 |\n",
        "| None | 2 | 0.52 |\n",
        "| None | 10 | 0.49 |\n",
        "| None | 50 | 0.46 |\n",
        "| None | 100 | 0.45 |"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "6jRD5RobpPd7"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**Note:** the MSE values are **illustrative** only but we expect to see a similar pattern to that shown above: very shallow trees underfit, unconstrained trees overfit, intermediate depth wins."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "HI96c7zVpQxE"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**The validation MSE is a proxy for out-of-sample performance: the grid search finds the combination that generalises best to your specific data, without ever touching the test set.**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "CoxjLt7upjCS"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "for max_depth in dt_param_grid[\"max_depth\"]:\n",
        "    for min_samples_split in dt_param_grid[\"min_samples_split\"]:\n",
        "      fold_mses = []\n",
        "      for fold, (train_idx, val_idx) in enumerate(tscv.split(X_train_val), 1):\n",
        "\n",
        "        #Prepare the various datasets\n",
        "        X_train_fold, X_validation_fold = X_train_val.iloc[train_idx], X_train_val.iloc[val_idx]\n",
        "        y_train_fold, y_validation_fold = y_train_val.iloc[train_idx], y_train_val.iloc[val_idx]\n",
        "\n",
        "        #Scale correctly the features (numeric only)\n",
        "        X_train_fold_mean = X_train_fold[numeric_cols].mean()\n",
        "        X_train_fold_std  = X_train_fold[numeric_cols].std(ddof=0)\n",
        "        X_train_fold_scaled = X_train_fold.copy()\n",
        "        X_validation_fold_scaled = X_validation_fold.copy()\n",
        "        X_train_fold_scaled[numeric_cols] = (X_train_fold[numeric_cols] - X_train_fold_mean) / X_train_fold_std\n",
        "        X_validation_fold_scaled[numeric_cols] = (X_validation_fold[numeric_cols] - X_train_fold_mean) / X_train_fold_std\n",
        "\n",
        "        #Scale correctly the target\n",
        "        y_train_fold_mean = y_train_fold.mean()\n",
        "        y_train_fold_std  = y_train_fold.std(ddof=0)\n",
        "        y_train_fold_scaled = (y_train_fold - y_train_fold_mean) / y_train_fold_std\n",
        "        y_validation_fold_scaled = (y_validation_fold - y_train_fold_mean) / y_train_fold_std\n",
        "\n",
        "        #Train the model for combination of hyperparameters + fold\n",
        "        model = DecisionTreeRegressor(max_depth=max_depth, min_samples_split=min_samples_split, random_state=42)\n",
        "        model.fit(X_train_fold_scaled, y_train_fold_scaled)\n",
        "\n",
        "        #Predict\n",
        "        y_pred_scaled = model.predict(X_validation_fold_scaled)\n",
        "\n",
        "        #Inverse-scale the predictions\n",
        "        y_pred = y_pred_scaled * y_train_fold_std + y_train_fold_mean\n",
        "\n",
        "        #Calculate the MSE for the fold\n",
        "        fold_mses.append(mean_squared_error(y_validation_fold, y_pred))\n",
        "\n",
        "      #Average the MSE over folds\n",
        "      avg_mse = np.mean(fold_mses)\n",
        "      dt_results.append({\n",
        "            \"model\": \"DecisionTree\",\n",
        "            \"max_depth\": max_depth,\n",
        "            \"min_samples_split\": min_samples_split,\n",
        "            \"average mse across 5 folds\": avg_mse\n",
        "        })\n",
        "\n",
        "dt_results_df = pd.DataFrame(dt_results)\n",
        "best_dt = dt_results_df.loc[dt_results_df[\"average mse across 5 folds\"].idxmin()]\n",
        "print(\"Best DecisionTreeRegressor hyperparameters:\")\n",
        "print(best_dt)"
      ],
